04923nam a22007215i 9780824845360DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248453607 a10.1515/97808248453602doi  a(DE-B1597)483757  a(OCoLC)1041973996  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aART0190002bisacsh0481pa320qDE-1011 aWong, Aida Yuen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParting the Mists :bDiscovering Japan and the Rise of National-Style Painting in Modern China /cAida Yuen Wong. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b64 illus., 30 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- t1. Tradition Is a Foreign Country -- t2. Nationalism and the Writing of New Histories -- t3. Literati Painting as the “Oriental Modern” -- t4. Wu Changshuo’s Japanese Circle: Between Patronage and Style -- t5. Six Exhibitions and Sino-Japanese Diplomacy -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Parting the Mists, Aida Yuen Wong makes a convincing argument that the forging of a national tradition in modern China was frequently pursued in association with rather than in rejection of Japan. The focus of her book is on Japan’s integral role in the invention of "national-style painting," or guohua, in early-twentieth-century China. Guohua, referring to brush paintings on traditional formats, is often misconstrued as a residual conservatism from the dynastic age that barricaded itself within classical traditions. Wong places this art form at the forefront of cross-cultural exchange. Notable proponents of guohua (e.g., Chen Hengke, Jin Cheng, Fu Baoshi, and Gao Jianfu) are discussed in connection with Japan, where they discovered stylistic and ideological paradigms consonant with the empowering of "Asian/Oriental" cultural practices against the backdrop of encroaching westernization. Not just a "window on the West," Japan stood as an informant of China modernism in its own right.The first book in English devoted to Sino-Japanese dialogues in modern art, Parting the Mists explores the sensitive phenomenon of Japanism in the practice and theory of Chinese painting. Wong carries out a methodologically agile study that sheds light on multiple spheres: stylistic and iconographic innovations, history writing, art theory, patronage and the market, geopolitics, the creation of artists’ societies, and exhibitions. Without avoiding the dark history of Japanese imperialism, she provides a nuanced reading of Chinese views about Japan and the two countries’ convergent, and often colliding, courses of nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484536040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824845360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824845360/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_E